\section{The azimuthal dependence of  neutrinoproduction.}
The dependence of a leptoproduction  cross section on azimuthal angles is a  widely used way to analyze the scattering mechanism. This procedure is helpful as soon as one can define an angle $\varphi$ between a leptonic and a hadronic plane, as for deeply virtual Compton scattering \cite{DGPR} and related processes. In the neutrino case, it reads :
\begin{eqnarray}
\label{cs}
\frac{d^4\sigma(\nu N\to l^- N'D)}{dx_B\, dQ^2\, dt\,  d\varphi}&=&

\\
 \tilde\Gamma
\Bigl\{ ~\frac{1+ \sqrt{1-\varepsilon^2}}{2} \sigma_{- -}&+&\varepsilon\sigma_{00}+  \sqrt{\varepsilon}(\sqrt{1+\varepsilon}+\sqrt{1-\varepsilon} )(\cos\varphi\
{\rm Re}\sigma_{- 0} + \sin\varphi\
 {\rm Im}\sigma_{- 0} )\ \Bigr\},\nonumber
\end{eqnarray}
with

